msgctxt "info/squad/squad_light(ger)"
msgid "Light infantry squad"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/snipers(usa)"
msgid "Using his rifle a sniper can eliminate enemy personnel from a safe distance and spot hiding enemy saboteurs using the rifle's mounted telescopic sight. Camouflage is the sniper's main weapon. That is why, in addition to his scoped Springfield rifle, he carries a throwing knife and several camouflaging bushes."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_shock(rus)"
msgid "Shock Inf."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_reserve(ger)"
msgid "Reserves"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_rifleaut(ger)"
msgid "Semi-auto Inf."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/mk8"
msgid "One of the most widely used British cruiser tanks entered mass production in January 1943 and was the modified version of the Crusader tank. The turret-mounted 75mm gun was unable to penetrate frontal armor of the newest German tanks, however the Mk.VIII Cromwell was respected by tank crews for its speed and manoeuvrability. The tank was designed for quick penetration deep into enemy territory and strategic initiative support."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_guards(rus)"
msgid "When one of the frontline divisions achieved corageous success in the ongoing battles, the USSR high command granted them the honorary position of Guards of the Soviet Union. They were prioritised when considering the operation battle plans, likewise they were usually better equipped. <c(DB465A)>Soviet Guard divisions have more experience in battle and better equipment than regular regular infantry, and they carry a MG in the squad for suppession.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/riflemans(ger)"
msgid "A team of six soldiers, each armed with two anti-personnel grenades and a Mauser rifle. The rifle's long range make the squad most effective over long and medium distances. However, due to the Mauser's low-capacity cartridge and a low rate of fire, at close range those riflemen are easy targets for submachine gunners and assault infantry."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_rifle(ger)"
msgid "Rifleman"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_paratrooper(rus)"
msgid "Soviet Paratroopers of the start of WW2 saw action in the Winter War and in several behind enemy line operations of WW2. They are, therefore, trained for versatile operations that include sabotage, assassination, combat, etc. <c(DB465A)>Soviet Paratroopers are a compromise between sabotage and frontline combat. They are semi-stealthy and carry deadly satchels and molotovs, but they also wield light semi-automatic weapons for short to medium range encounters. They also sprint faster to be able to be able to ensure swift 'boom and zooms'. To fully maaximise their potential they do require careful micro-control.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/universal_carrier_rus"
msgid "The Universal Carrier, also known (incorrectly) as the Bren Gun Carrier is a common name describing a family of light armored tracked vehicles built by Vickers-Armstrong. Produced between 1934 and 1960, the vehicle was used widely by British Commonwealth forces during the Second World War. Universal Carriers were usually used for transporting personnel and equipment, mostly support weapons, or as machine gun platforms. With some 113,000 built in the United Kingdom and abroad, it was the most produced armored fighting vehicle in history"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/entity/gmc_art"
msgid "In the inventory of these trucks you will find armor-piercing and high explosive rounds, crates to carry them, and a repair kit. \n This army truck was an upgraded version of the civilian ACX-353. During the war these vehicles were used for transporting cargo, relocating troops towing artillery. Some modifications could be used as gasoline tankers."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_medic(ger)"
msgid "Medic"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_heavy(ger)"
msgid "Regular Inf."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_engineer(ger)"
msgid "Field engineer"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/pz6e"
msgid "Entered service with the German army in 1942 and was considered the best tank until the end of 1943. Soviet 45mm guns could not penetrate the Tiger's armor even at point-blank range, while its 88mm gun was able to destroy any tank of the times."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/homeguard(usa)"
msgid "The American Home Guard"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_smg(ger)"
msgid "MP-40 soldier"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_miners(usa)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment zones from enemy vehicles and tanks and are mainly used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine laying specialists is armed with Thompson submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_mg(ger)"
msgid "MG Detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/flamers(eng)"
msgid "A soldier armed with a flame-thrower can inflict heavy damage on infantry inside a building and can single-handedly clear an entire area of enemies. In spite of this, he is extremely vulnerable because once he has used up all of his flammable liquid he remains unarmed and a random bullet can cause an explosion if it hits his cylinder. Accordingly, a combat unit includes several escort submachine gunners."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/ap_miners(ger)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment zones from enemy vehicles and tanks and are mainly used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine laying specialists is armed with MP-40 submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_at_miner(ger)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment zones from enemy vehicles and tanks and are mainly used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine laying specialists is armed with MP-40 submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_ap_miner(ger)"
msgid "AP Miner"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/bazookers(usa)"
msgid "The portable anti-tank rocket launcher Bazooka was designed to fight enemy equipment and could actually put any tank out of action if used skilfully. The damage capacity of a high-explosion grenade is not reduced over distance, but rocket launchers are still most efficient at close and medium range. It is very difficult to hit a target when firing a Bazooka at long range. An infantryman carrying a rocket launcher is extremely vulnerable which is why a combat unit includes a submachine gunner to escort and cover him."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_at(ger)"
msgid "AT Detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_engineer(rus)"
msgid "Field engineer"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_at_44(ger)"
msgid "AT Detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_medic(rus)"
msgid "Medic"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_flamer(ger)"
msgid "Flamer"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_rifle(eng)"
msgid "Boys AT, the British anti-tank rifle, was adopted in November 1937. Since its killing power was rather low – a 60-gram bullet could pierce up to 15mm of armor – such rifles were only used against light-armored targets. This rifle couldn't destroy a medium or heavy tank, it could only knock off a track or damage a gun."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/vickers"
msgid "Not Familiar with this thing."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/scouts(rus)"
msgid "The saboteur is a well-trained soldier capable of single-handedly inflicting devastating damage on the enemy. He can hide in bushes or tall grass and stay almost invisible while crawling. He is armed with a silenced pistol, several throwing knives, an incendiary grenade and an explosive charge powerful enough to turn the heaviest tanks into a heap of scrap metal."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_sniper(ger)"
msgid "Sniper"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_officer(ger)"
msgid "Officer"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_basic(rus)"
msgid "The light infantry composes the basic structure of Soviet rushed recruitment and deployment of troops during WW2. <c(DB465A)>The squad leader carries a sub-machinegun and a few grenades while the standard squad members have ordinary rifles.</c>]"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_volkssturm(ger)"
msgid "The Volkssturm were civilians armed with small amounts of ammunition and cheap weaponry, including the infamous Panzerfaust AT shaped charge rockets, with the purpose of being the last line of defense of the Fatherland. They composed a weak but nonetheless relevant defense, inflicting damage upon the advancing troops in Germany at the end of the war. The command of these groups fell in the hands of the SS and Nazi political figureheards, significantly reducing it's potential as an efficient fighting force.<c(DB465A)> They are a good last resort unit for desperate measures, but do not expect miracles from these troops.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/vickers_mgun"
msgid "The Vickers medium machine gun appeared in 1912 in Great Britain as a modification of the famous Maxim gun and was used by the British Army until the 1960s. The machine gun offered an excellent rate of fire at long range but its heavy weight made transportation difficult."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_mg(rus)"
msgid "MG Detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_pioneer(ger)"
msgid "The Pioniere squads are the top of the Wehrmacht infantry spearhead, and they were greately respected and admired by the High Command. <c(DB465A)>They carry flamethrowers, grenades and other demolition equipment. Their specialty: Dealing with the enemy frontline fortifications face to face. Provided they can reach the enemy strongholds through the open ground, mayhem shall spread as the demolitions begin."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_basic(ger)"
msgid "Light Inf."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/mk4"
msgid "The first production models of a new infantry support tank appeared in June 1941. The design was to replace the Mk.II \"Matilda\", which was quickly becoming obsolete, but due to a short development cycle it was sent to production with a range of defects. The tank had a low profile and strong armor, but its extremely weak armament negated these advantages. Further modifications did not help - a newly mounted 75mm gun did not improve its anti-tank capabilities leaving the Mk.IV with the role of an infantry support vehicle."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_militia(rus)"
msgid "In the time of the German invasion of the USSR, the borders were often guarded by border militia. They were part of the Army, yet they were not trained nor armed as much as regular army forces. Some of them wore civilian clothing<c(DB465A)>Their simple armament consisting of rifles without additional grenades nor automatic weapons makes them adequate at medium to long range encounters, but by all means they are not trained to engage any elite infantry that opposes it. Use them strategically to cover holes in your defense line, their low price and low CP enables them to be fielded easily.</c>]"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/bazookers(eng)"
msgid "In 1942, Great Britain started manufacturing its own anti-tank rocket launchers to replace its inefficient anti-tank rifles. A shaped charge fired from a PIAT could burn through a 120mm armor plate, allowing it to destroy almost any enemy vehicle. Since firing accuracy was greatly reduced at long distances, rocket launchers were most effective at close and medium range. An infantryman armed with a rocket launcher was very vulnerable. For this reason, such a squad also included a submachine gunner to cover him."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_flamer(rus)"
msgid "Flamer"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/officer(rus)"
msgid "The presence of a veteran officer on the battlefield can turn the course of any battle. Using his field binoculars he can spot enemy infantry and saboteurs hiding in bushes and tall grass. The officer can also spot enemy units at a distance allowing you to regroup and react ahead of time. Besides his binoculars, he also carries a knife and a Nagant pistol. These weapons are poorly suited for a heated battle."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_luftwaffe(ger)"
msgid "The Luftwaffe field units were deployed to give frontline support to the Wehrmacht as well as protecting the airfields on the combat zone from land raids. <c(DB465A)>They are not the most resilient of soldiers and they are not trained like other elites, but they are staggeringly deadly with their choice of equipment: AT weaponry against enemy vehicles and aircraft-based MG15's, which provide second-to-none accurate suppression. A great unit for defensive means.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_sturm_p(ger)"
msgid "Sturmpioniere are motorised Pioneers under the command of the Panzerwaffe (Tank corps). <c(DB465A)>They come on board a Hanomag.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_miners(ger)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment sites and are mainly placed before the occupied position, occasionally on the flanks. A group of four mine-laying specialists is armed with MP-40 submachine guns and capable of quickly deploying the obstacle line, thereby securing disputable or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/tankmans(ger)"
msgid "The effectiveness of a tank depends first of all on the cohesion of the crew and its ability to act consistently in any situation. The most powerful and dangerous machine will become just a pile of scrap if the people controlling it suddenly disappear. When training a tank crew, complete cross-training of all members is key because the tank must remain battle-worthy even if only one crew member survives... \n Although tank crews are armed with compact MP-40 submachine guns, they have no combat training and are hence extremely vulnerable."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_brandenburger(ger)"
msgid "The Brandenburger commandos were stealth units trained in foreign languages, combat and demolition tasks. They were fielded during the war for the most perilous undercover tasks, from detonating bridges and sabotaging the enemy to switching the entire road directions on the enemy territory to confuse the foes. <c(DB465A)>They carry detonation equipment and good weaponry, and they are both fast runners and stealthy.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_fallschirmjaeger(ger)"
msgid "The Fallschirmjger (paratroopers) were considered the best german combat-trained unit and during the war they single-handedly undertook operations such as the assault of fort Eban-Emael, the capture of Crete and the defense of Monte-Cassino. After the capture of Crete, Hitler ordered no more large scale paradropping operations in risk of loosing too many of his elite.<c(DB465A)> They are solid all-round, and their squads incorporate from MG gunners to snipers. Towards the end of the war they became even more lethal with FG-42 automatic rifles and Panzerfausts.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_gebirgsjaeger(ger)"
msgid "The German Gebirgsjger were mountain troops prepared to face the enemy on the most troublesome terrain and perilous circumstances. Their unrivaled strong point is that they train to be able to travel long distances without rest. Wherever they are sent to, they will arrive quickly and ready for combat wielding their Edelweiss emblem.<c(DB465A)> They are equipped with lighter rifles and their main man carries an MG34 with a double drum configuration, able to unload double the ammunition in every reload.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_miners(rus)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment zones from enemy vehicles and tanks and are mainly used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine laying specialists is armed with PPSh submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/entity/machinegewehr_34_no_bipod_belt"
msgid "The MG-34 entered service with the Wehrmacht in 1934 and was used in hand, mounted, anti-aircraft and tank variants. An MG mounted on a tripod was able to fire at both ground and airborne targets. While it surpassed its Western counterparts in terms of rate of fire, continuous fire caused the machine gun's barrel to overheat quickly."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_ss_grenadiers(ger)"
msgid "The SS grenadiers formed a reliable bulk of the german forces on the late years of the war and they were prepared to receive any orders. The fresh SS troops of 1944-45 were lightly trained but their impact on combat came down to having received the best armament the german industry was rushing, including STG-44 assault rifles and Panzerfaust anti-tank weapons. <c(DB465A)>They form a compact squad which is versatile in combat, able to attack, hold positions with sustained fire, and destroy enemy tanks.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_tankman(rus)"
msgid "Tank Crew"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_rifle(rus)"
msgid "Rifleman"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_smg(rus)"
msgid "PPSH trooper"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_rifleauto(rus)"
msgid "SVT Marksman"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_ap_miner(rus)"
msgid "AP Miner"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/pz5g"
msgid "The Ausf.G Panther version was created as a response to the Soviet T34, and entered mass production in March 1944. Its relatively good manoeuvrability and a long-barrelled 75mm gun made the tank a dangerous adversary. Its insufficient side protection was compensated with excellent frontal armor."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_at_miner(rus)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment zones from enemy vehicles and tanks and are mainly used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine laying specialists is armed with MP-40 submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/entity/d1"
msgid "Soviet heavy artillery field howitzer of 152mm calibre, capable of high Explosive and smoke rounds. \n The 152mm howitzer entered service with the Red Army on August 8th, 1943. It was designed for indirect firing at enemy personnel, fortifications and trench lines. The D-1 was considered equal to world's best guns of its class and its mobility, range and the destructive force of high-explosive rounds have made it an almost perfect weapon of its times. On the battlefield it earned its reputation for being a reliable and accurate artillery piece boasting excellent ballistic characteristics and high mobility."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_at(rus)"
msgid "AT Detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_sappers(rus)"
msgid "Assault Sappers"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_supply(rus)"
msgid "Supply detach."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_officer(rus)"
msgid "Commissar"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_sniper(rus)"
msgid "Sniper"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_single_sabotage(rus)"
msgid "SMERSH soldier"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/pz6bh"
msgid "Entered service with the Wehrmacht in 1944. Its turret-mounted 88mm long-barrelled gun was capable of destroying any enemy tank from a long distance. In combination with its excellent armor, this made the King Tiger the most powerful tank of WWII. The Pz VI ausf.B is almost invulnerable to enemy guns, but its 70t weight has negative impact on its mobility."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/bazookers(rus)"
msgid "The portable rocket launcher Bazooka was developed by US designers to fight enemy equipment. Some of them were delivered to the Soviet Union under the Lend-Lease program. Although the damage capacity of a high-explosion grenade is not reduced over distance, rocket launchers are most efficient at close and medium range. It is very difficult to hit a target when firing a bazooka at long range. An infantryman carrying a rocket launcher is extremely vulnerable which is why a combat unit includes a submachine gunner to cover him."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/smgs(ger)"
msgid "Soldiers are armed with MP-40 submachine guns, clusters of MP24 grenades to fight armored vehicles and several anti-personnel fragmentation grenades. Such squads are highly effective at fighting enemy infantry at close and medium range and accordingly can be used both to storm enemy positions and to repel enemy attacks."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_partisans(rus)"
msgid "Partisans were civilians armed with weapons from home, the enemy or dead comrades. They stood up against the German invasion and are willying to fight until the last breath for their burnt villages or dead families. <c(DB465A)>They are not trained for face to face combat unlike the army troops but they are ideal for ambushes, surprise attacks and they are inexpensive.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_rifle(ger)"
msgid "This German anti-tank rifle was put into service with the Wehrmacht in 1939 and was the main infantry combat tool against light armored equipment before Panzerfausts were introduced. Its 14.5g bullet with tungsten core could pierce a 20mm armored plate when shot at medium range. This enabled the Panzerbushe 39 to establish en excellent reputation at the beginning of World War 2. However, with the advent of Matildas and T-34 the effectiveness of the rifle dropped significantly because at best it could only knock the tracks from these tanks or damage their guns. An anti-armor crew consists of two people."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_miners(eng)"
msgid "Anti-tank minefields are primarily meant for securing troop deployment sites and are mainly placed in front of established positions and occasionally on the flanks. A group of four mine-laying specialists, armed with M3A1 submachine guns, is capable of quickly deploying the obstacle line, thereby securing unoccupied or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_nkvd(rus)"
msgid "In 1941, the NKVD started recruiting criminals or convicted men in the USSR to form the infamous penal batallions. The convicts were given a chance to clean their crimes with blood by advancing into the enemy territory in massive suicidal attacks. Upon retreating, they would also get shot from their own NKVD commanders. <c(DB465A)>These troops are not very well armed and they do not carry plenty of ammunition. What counts is their sheer numbers and the ability to deploy them without extensive costs.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_heavy(rus)"
msgid "The Heavy infantry squad was what the Soviet doctrines of the war demanded as the standard, but due to the constant losses and disorganisation after the sudden German invasion, the squads were often not fully fledged as per what was written on the book.<c(DB465A)>Heavy or full squads incorporate a MG gunner with it's assistant and thus grants a good suppression tool against the enemy compared to the light infantry.</c>"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/ap_miners(eng)"
msgid "Anti-personnel minefields are intended to deny enemy personnel entry to deployment sites and are mainly placed in front of established positions or on the flanks. A group of four mine-laying soldiers, armed with M3A1 submachine guns, is capable of quick deployment of minefields, thereby securing unoccupied or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_marines(rus)"
msgid "Black Jackets"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/mp_squad_spetsnaz(rus)"
msgid "Osnaz Unit"
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/ap_miners(rus)"
msgid "Anti-personnel minefields are intended to deny enemy personnel entry to deployment sites and are usually used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine-laying specialists is armed with PPSh submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/tortez"
msgid "The Tortoise was the result of a heavy assault tank development process that began in Britain in 1942. Its heavy weight impaired its mobility, but it was decided that speed did not play a major role during the clearing of fortified positions. The hull, composed of rolled armor plates, could multiple direct hits and its upgraded anti-aircraft gun could successfully defeat German tanks. However, due to its long development cycle the A39 did not see action in WWII."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/ap_miners(usa)"
msgid "Anti-personnel minefields are intended to deny enemy personnel entry to deployment sites and are usually used in front of occupied positions or to guard one's flanks. A group of four mine-laying specialists is armed with Thompson submachine guns and is capable of quickly laying minefields, thereby securing disputed or strategically important sectors."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/entity/kubel_mgun"
msgid "Production of this light off-road vehicle began in 1940. Thanks to its simplicity and reliability, the Kubelwagen soon added its name to the list of the most famous vehicles of World War 2, becoming one of the symbols of the German Army. Its air-cooled engine worked as well in hot African conditions as in freezing Russia, while its low vehicle weight had a positive effect on its cross-country ability. Some modifications were equipped with a vertical bar with a machine gun mount."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/entity/hummel"
msgid "The Hummel self-propelled heavy 150mm howitzer entered service with the Wehrmacht in May 1943 and was designed to demolish enemy fortifications and provide support to assault groups. Its low ordnance capacity along with thin, open-top armor made it unsuitable for close combat. In spite of this, the \"Bumblebee\" was a fearsome weapon, capable of dealing tremendous damage to the enemy."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/bazookers(ger)"
msgid "The portable anti-tank Panzerschreck was an expensive but powerful weapon, vastly superior to the American Bazooka in terms of its piercing performance. The damage capacity of a high-explosion grenade is not reduced over distance but rocket launchers are still most efficient at close and medium range. It is very difficult to hit a target when firing such a weapon at long range. An infantry man carrying a rocket launcher is extremely vulnerable which is why a combat unit includes an escort submachine gunner."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/at_rifle(rus)"
msgid "This anti-tank rifle designed by Simonov entered service with the Red Army on 29 August, 1941 and was put into mass production shortly afterwards. It differed from other models due to its increased weight and self-loading feed system. In the early days of the war, this weapon was used to fight all types of German equipment but over time its effectiveness dropped noticeably. In the later stages of the war an anti-tank rifle could no longer destroy medium and heavy enemy tanks but was only able to damage their tracks and guns. A PTRS crew consists of two people."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/elite(eng)"
msgid "Commando special purpose troops were formed at Churchill's initiative in June 1940 for reconnaissance and sabotage actions in the enemy's rear and for the most critical assault operations. Commandos were armed with American Thompson submachine guns, Bren light machine guns as well as smoke, anti-personnel and anti-tank grenades. Commando squads were considered elite by right – their excellent training and impressive arsenal guaranteed effective military action in all conditions."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/elite(ger)"
msgid "German airborne troops came into being in 1935 and took part in a number of assault operations at the beginning of World War 2. Unlike similar units in other countries, German paratroopers did not belong to the special forces and were, as a matter of fact, well-trained infantry operating in the air. Those fearless fighters were armed with anti-tank, anti-personnel and smoke grenades, dynamite sticks, knives, submachine guns and FG 42 assault rifles which enabled them to fight effectively in all conditions."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/elite(rus)"
msgid "Red Banner marine battalions were staffed with sailors and officers of the USSR Navy. Those brave and tough soldiers were sent to the most dangerous areas of the front where the harsh battles they fought made them deserving of the status of Soviet elite troops. Marines are fearless and well armed. Their self-loading rifles designed by Tokarev boast an excellent firing rate and the large number of anti-tank, anti-personnel and smoke grenades available to them enables them to effectively fight in all conditions."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/elite(usa)"
msgid "Ranger units were developed in the USA in 1942 to perform reconnaissance and sabotage tasks in the Pacific and in Africa. They could be landed by air or sea while their arsenal included anti-tank, anti-personnel and smoke grenades, M1A1 semi-automatic carbines, Thompson submachine guns and dynamite sticks. These armaments enabled special forces to fight effectively both in the enemy’s rear and on the front line."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/flamers(ger)"
msgid "A soldier armed with a flame-thrower can inflict heavy damage on infantry inside a building and can single-handedly clear an entire area of enemies. In spite of this, he is extremely vulnerable because once he has used up all of his flammable liquid he remains unarmed and a random bullet can cause an explosion if it hits his cylinder. Accordingly, a combat unit includes several escort submachine gunners."
msgstr ""

msgctxt "info/squad/flamers(rus)"
msgid "A soldier armed with a flame-thrower can inflict heavy damage on infantry inside a building and can single-handedly clear an entire area of enemies. In spite of this, he is extremely vulnerable because once he has used up all of his flammable liquid he remains unarmed and a random bullet can cause an explosion if it hits his cylinder. Accordingly, a combat unit includes several escort submachine gunners."
msgstr ""

